9 "§ 90B-27. Military families.
10 An active military member or their spouses shall designate a home state where the individual
11 has a multistate license. The individual may retain their home state designation during the period
12 the service member is on active duty.
13 "§ 90B-28. Adverse action.
14 (a) In addition to the other powers conferred by state law, a remote state shall have the
15 authority, in accordance with existing state due process law, to do the following:
16 (1) Take adverse action against a regulated social worker's multistate
17 authorization to practice only within that member state, and issue subpoenas
18 for both hearings and investigations that require the attendance and testimony
19 of witnesses as well as the production of evidence. Subpoenas issued by a
20 licensing authority in a member state for the attendance and testimony of
21 witnesses or the production of evidence from another member state shall be
22 enforced in the latter state by any court of competent jurisdiction, according
23 to the practice and procedure of that court applicable to subpoenas issued in
24 proceedings pending before it. The issuing authority shall pay any witness
25 fees, travel expenses, mileage, and other fees required by the service statutes
26 of the state in which the witnesses or evidence are located.
27 (2) Only the home state shall have the power to take adverse action against a
28 regulated social worker's multistate license.
29 (b) For purposes of taking adverse action, the home state shall give the same priority and
30 effect to reported conduct received from a member state as it would if the conduct had occurred
31 within the home state. In so doing, the home state shall apply its own state laws to determine
32 appropriate action.
33 (c) The home state shall complete any pending investigations of a regulated social worker
34 who changes their home state during the course of the investigations. The home state shall also
35 have the authority to take appropriate action and shall promptly report the conclusions of the
36 investigations to the administrator of the data system. The administrator of the data system shall
37 promptly notify the new home state of any adverse actions.
38 (d) A member state, if otherwise permitted by state law, may recover from the affected
39 regulated social worker the costs of investigations and dispositions of cases resulting from any
40 adverse action taken against that regulated social worker.
41 (e) A member state may take adverse action based on the factual findings of another
42 member state, provided that the member state follows its own procedures for taking the adverse
43 action.
44 (f) Joint investigations:
45 (1) In addition to the authority granted to a member state by its respective social
46 work practice act or other applicable state law, any member state may
47 participate with other member states in joint investigations of licensees.
48 (2) Member states shall share any investigative, litigation, or compliance
49 materials in furtherance of any joint or individual investigation initiated under
50 the Compact.
