39 (1) The Executive Committee shall be composed of 11 members, as follows:
40 a. The chair and vice-chair of the Commission shall be voting members
41 of the Executive Committee.
42 b. Five voting members who are elected by the Commission from the
43 current membership of the Commission.
44 c. Up to four ex officio, nonvoting members from four recognized
45 national social work organizations, selected by their respective
46 organizations.
47 (3) The Commission may remove any member of the Executive Committee as
48 provided in the bylaws.
49 (4) The Executive Committee shall meet at least annually.
50 (5) Executive Committee meetings shall be open to the public, except that the
51 Executive Committee may meet in a closed, nonpublic meeting as provided
Page 10 House Bill 231-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 by this Article. The Executive Committee shall give seven days' notice of its
2 meetings, posted on its website and as determined to provide notice to persons
3 with an interest in the business of the Commission. The Executive Committee
4 may hold a special meeting in accordance with this Article.
5 (6) The Executive Committee shall have the power to act on behalf of the
6 Commission according to the terms of the Compact. The Commission shall
7 have the following powers, duties, and responsibilities:
8 a. Oversee the day-to-day activities of the administration of the Compact,
9 including enforcement and compliance with the provisions of the
10 Compact, its rules and bylaws, and other such duties as deemed
11 necessary.
12 b. Recommend to the Commission changes to the rules or bylaws,
13 changes to this Compact legislation, fees charged to Compact member
14 states, fees charged to licensees, and other fees.
15 c. Ensure Compact administration services are appropriately provided,
16 including by contract.
17 d. Prepare and recommend the budget.
18 e. Maintain financial records on behalf of the Commission.
19 f. Monitor Compact compliance of member states and provide
20 compliance reports to the Commission.
21 g. Establish additional committees as necessary.
22 h. Exercise the powers and duties of the Commission during the interim
23 between Commission meetings, except for adopting or amending
24 rules, adopted or amending bylaws, and exercising any other powers
25 and duties expressly reserved to the Commission by rule or bylaw.
26 i. Perform other duties as provided in rules or bylaws of the
27 Commission.
28 (e) Meetings of the Commission. – All meetings shall be open to the public, and public
29 notice of meetings shall be given in the same manner as required under the rulemaking provisions
30 in G.S. 90B-31. The Commission may hold a special meeting when it must meet to conduct
31 emergency business by giving 48 hours' notice to all commissioners, on the Commission's
32 website, and other means as provided in the Commission's rules. The Commission's legal counsel
33 shall certify that the Commission's need to meet qualifies as an emergency. The Commission or
34 the Executive Committee or other committees of the Commission may convene in a closed,
35 nonpublic meeting if the Commission or Executive Committee or other committees of the
36 Commission must receive legal advice or discuss any of the following:
37 (1) Noncompliance of a member state with its obligations under the Compact.
38 (2) The employment, compensation, discipline, or other matters, practices, or
39 procedures related to specific employees or other matters related to the
40 Commission's internal personnel practices and procedures.
41 (3) Current, threatened, or reasonably anticipated litigation.
42 (4) Negotiation of contracts for the purchase, lease, or sale of goods, services, or
43 real estate.
44 (5) Accusation of any person of a crime or formally censuring any person.
45 (6) Disclosure of trade secrets or commercial or financial information that is
46 privileged or confidential.
47 (7) Disclosure of information of a personal nature where disclosure would
48 constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.
49 (8) Disclosure of investigative records compiled for law enforcement purposes.
50 (9) Disclosure of information related to any investigative reports prepared by or
51 on behalf of or for use of the Commission or other committee charged with
House Bill 231-First Edition Page 11

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 responsibility of investigation or determination of compliance issues pursuant
2 to the Compact.
3 (10) Matters specifically exempted from disclosure by federal or member state
4 statute.
5 (11) Current or threatened discipline of a licensee by the Commission or by a
6 member state's licensing authority.
7 (12) Other matters as promulgated by the Commission by rule.
8 If a meeting, or portion of a meeting, is closed pursuant to this provision, the Commission's
9 presiding officer shall state that the meeting will be closed and shall reference each relevant
10 exempting provision, and such reference shall be recorded in the minutes. The Commission shall
11 keep minutes that fully and clearly describe all matters discussed in a meeting and shall provide
12 a full and accurate summary of actions taken, and the reasons therefore, including a description
13 of the views expressed. All documents considered in connection with an action shall be identified
14 in such minutes. All minutes and documents of a closed meeting shall remain under seal, subject
15 to release by a majority vote of the Commission or order of a court of competent jurisdiction.
16 (f) Financing of the Commission. – The Commission shall pay, or provide for the
17 payment of, the reasonable expenses of its establishment, organization, and ongoing activities.
18 The Commission may accept any and all appropriate revenue sources, donations, and grants of
19 money, equipment, supplies, materials, and services.
20 The Commission may levy on and collect an annual assessment from each member state and
21 impose fees on other licensees of member states to whom it grants a multistate license to cover
22 the cost of the operations and activities of the Commission and its staff, which must be in a total
23 amount sufficient to cover its annual budget as approved by the Commission each year for which
24 revenue is not provided by other sources. The aggregate annual assessment amount shall be
25 allocated based upon a formula to be determined by the Commission, which shall be promulgated
26 by rule. The Commission shall not incur obligations of any kind prior to securing the funds
27 adequate to meet the same; nor shall the Commission pledge the credit of any of the member
28 states, except by and with the authority of the member state.
29 The Commission shall keep accurate accounts of all receipts and disbursements. The receipts
30 and disbursements of the Commission shall be subject to the audit and accounting procedures
31 established under its bylaws. However, all receipts and disbursements of funds handled by the
32 Commission shall be audited yearly by a certified or licensed public accountant, and the report
33 of the audit shall be included in and become part of the annual report of the Commission.
34 (g) Qualified Immunity; Defense; Indemnification. – The members, officers, executive
35 director, employees, and representatives of the Commission shall be immune from suit and
36 liability, either personally or in their official capacity, for any claim for damage to or loss of
37 property or personal injury or other civil liability caused by or arising out of any actual or alleged
38 act, error, or omission that occurred, or that the person against whom the claim is made had a
39 reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope of Commission employment, duties, or
40 responsibilities, provided that nothing in this paragraph shall be construed to protect any such
41 person from suit or liability for any damage, loss, injury, or liability caused by the intentional or
42 willful or wanton misconduct of that person. The procurement of insurance of any type by the
43 Commission shall not in any way compromise or limit the immunity granted hereunder.
44 The Commission shall defend any member, officer, executive director, employee, or
45 representative of the Commission in any civil action seeking to impose liability arising out of
46 any actual or alleged act, error, or omission that occurred within the scope of Commission
47 employment, duties, or responsibilities, or as determined by the Commission that the person
48 against whom the claim is made had a reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope
49 of Commission employment, duties, or responsibilities; provided that nothing herein shall be
50 construed to prohibit that person from retaining his or her own counsel at their own expense; and
Page 12 House Bill 231-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 provided further, that the actual or alleged act, error, or omission did not result from that person's
2 intentional or willful or wanton misconduct.
3 The Commission shall indemnify and hold harmless any member, officer, executive director,
4 employee, or representative of the Commission for the amount of any settlement or judgment
5 obtained against that person arising out of any actual or alleged act, error, or omission that
6 occurred within the scope of Commission employment, duties, or responsibilities, or that such
7 person had a reasonable basis for believing occurred within the scope of Commission
8 employment, duties, or responsibilities, provided that the actual or alleged act, error, or omission
9 did not result from the intentional or willful or wanton misconduct of that person.
10 Nothing herein shall be construed as a limitation on the liability of any licensee for
11 professional malpractice or misconduct, which shall be governed solely by any other applicable
12 state laws. Nothing in this Compact shall be interpreted to waive or otherwise abrogate a member
13 state's state action immunity or state action affirmative defense with respect to antitrust claims
14 under the Sherman Act, Clayton Act, or any other state or federal antitrust or anticompetitive law
15 or regulation. Nothing in this Compact shall be construed to be a waiver of sovereign immunity
16 by the member states or by the Commission.
17 "§ 90B-30. Data system.
18 (a) The Commission shall provide for the development, maintenance, operation, and
19 utilization of a coordinated database and reporting system containing licensure, adverse action,
20 and the presence of current significant investigative information on all licensed individuals in
21 member states.
22 (b) The Commission shall assign each applicant for a multistate license a unique
23 identifier, as determined by the rules of the Commission.
24 (c) Notwithstanding any other provision of state law to the contrary, a member state shall
25 submit a uniform data set to the data system on all individuals to whom this Compact is
26 applicable, as required by the rules of the Commission, including all of the following:
27 (1) Identifying information.
28 (2) Licensure data.
29 (3) Adverse actions against a license and information related thereto.
30 (4) Nonconfidential information related to alternative program participation, the
31 beginning and ending dates of such participation, and other information
32 related to such participation not made confidential under member state law.
33 (5) Any denial of application for licensure and the reasons for such denial.
34 (6) Other information that may facilitate the administration of this Compact, as
35 determined by the rules of the Commission.
36 (7) Current significant investigative information.
37 (d) The records and information provided to a member state pursuant to this Compact or
38 through the data system, when certified by the Commission or an agent thereof, shall constitute
39 the authenticated business records of the Commission and shall be entitled to any associated
40 hearsay exception in any relevant judicial, quasi-judicial, or administrative proceedings in a
41 member state.
42 (e) Current significant investigative information pertaining to a licensee in any member
43 state will only be available to other member states. It is the responsibility of the member states
44 to report any adverse action against a licensee and to monitor the database to determine whether
45 adverse action has been taken against a licensee. Adverse action information pertaining to a
46 licensee in any member state will be available to any other member state.
47 (f) Member states contributing information to the data system may designate information
48 that may not be shared with the public without the express permission of the contributing state.
49 (g) Any information submitted to the data system that is subsequently required to be
50 expunged by federal law or the laws of the member state contributing the information shall be
51 removed from the data system.
House Bill 231-First Edition Page 13

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 90B-31. Rulemaking.
2 (a) The Commission shall promulgate reasonable rules in order to achieve the purposes
3 of the Compact effectively and efficiently. A rule shall be invalid and have no force or effect
4 only if a court of competent jurisdiction holds that the rule is invalid because the Commission
5 exercised its rulemaking authority in a manner that is beyond the scope and purposes of the
6 Compact, or the powers granted hereunder, or based upon another applicable standard of review.
7 (b) The rules of the Commission shall have the force of law in each member state,
8 provided, however, that where the rules of the Commission conflict with the laws of the member
9 state that establish the member state's laws, regulations, and applicable standards that govern the
10 practice of social work as held by a court of competent jurisdiction, the rules of the Commission
11 shall be ineffective in that state to the extent of the conflict.
12 (c) The Commission shall exercise its rulemaking powers pursuant to the criteria set forth
13 in this section and the rules adopted thereunder. Rules shall become binding on the day following
14 adoption or the date specified in the rule or amendment, whichever is later.
15 (d) If a majority of the legislatures of the member states rejects a rule or a portion of a
16 rule, by enactment of a statute or resolution in the same manner used to adopt the Compact within
17 four years of the date of adoption of the rule, then such rule shall have no further force and effect
18 in any member state.
19 (e) Rules or amendments to the rules shall be adopted at a regular or special meeting of
20 the Commission.
21 (f) Prior to adoption of a proposed rule, the Commission shall hold a public hearing and
22 allow persons to provide oral and written comments, data, facts, opinions, and arguments.
23 (g) Prior to promulgation and adoption of rule by the Commission, and at least 30 days
24 in advance of the meeting at which the Commission will hold a public hearing on the proposed
25 rule, the Commission shall provide a notice of proposed rulemaking (i) on the website of the
26 Commission or other publicly accessible platform, (ii) to persons who have requested notice of
27 the Commission's notices of proposed rulemaking, and (iii) in such other ways as the Commission
28 may, by rule, specify.
29 (h) The notice of proposed rulemaking shall include all of the following:
30 (1) The time, date, and location of the public hearing at which the Commission
31 will hear public comments on the proposed rule and, if different, the proposed
32 time, date, and location of the meeting in which the rule will be considered
33 and voted upon.
34 (2) If the hearing is held via telecommunication, video conference, or other
35 electronic means, the Commission shall include the mechanism for access to
36 the hearing in the notice of proposed rulemaking.
37 (3) The text of the proposed rule or amendment and the reason for the proposed
38 rule.
39 (4) A request for comments on the proposed rule from any interested person.
40 (5) The manner in which interested persons may submit written comments.
41 (i) All hearings will be recorded. A copy of the recording and all written comments and
42 documents received by the Commission in response to the proposed rule shall be available to the
43 public.
44 (j) Nothing in this section shall be construed as requiring a separate hearing on each rule.
45 Rules may be grouped for the convenience of the Commission at hearings required by this
46 section.
47 (k) The Commission shall, by majority vote of all members, take final action on the
48 proposed rule based on the rulemaking record and the full text of the rule.
49 (1) The Commission may adopt changes to the proposed rule provided the
50 changes do not enlarge the original purpose of the proposed rule.
Page 14 House Bill 231-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) The Commission shall provide an explanation of the reasons for substantive
2 changes made to the proposed rule as well as reasons for substantive changes
3 not made that were recommended by commenters.
4 (3) The Commission shall determine a reasonable effective date for the rule.
5 Except for an emergency as provided in this section, the effective date of the
6 rule shall be no sooner than 30 days after issuing the notice that it adopted or
7 amended the rule.
8 (l) Upon determination that an emergency exists, the Commission may consider and
9 adopt an emergency rule with 48 hours' notice, with opportunity for comment, provided that the
10 usual rulemaking procedures provided in the Compact and in this section shall be retroactively
11 applied to the rule as soon as reasonably possible, in no event later than 90 days after the effective
12 date of the rule. For the purposes of this provision, an emergency rule is one that must be adopted
13 immediately in order to (i) meet an imminent threat to public health, safety, or welfare, (ii)
14 prevent a loss of Commission or member state funds, (iii) meet a deadline for the promulgation
15 of an administrative rule that is established by federal law or rule, or (iv) protect public health
16 and safety.
17 (m) The Commission or an authorized committee of the Commission may direct revisions
18 to a previously adopted rule or amendment for purposes of correcting typographical errors, errors
19 in format, errors in consistency, or grammatical errors. Public notice of any revisions shall be
20 posted on the website of the Commission. The revision shall be subject to challenge by any
21 person for a period of 30 days after posting. The revision may be challenged only on grounds
22 that the revision results in a material change to a rule. A challenge shall be made in writing and
23 delivered to the chair of the Commission prior to the end of the notice period. If no challenge is
24 made, the revision will take effect without further action. If the revision is challenged, the
25 revision may not take effect without the approval of the Commission.
26 (n) No member state's rulemaking requirements shall apply under this Compact.
27 "§ 90B-32. Oversight; dispute resolution; enforcement.
28 (a) The executive and judicial branches of state government in each member state shall
29 enforce this Compact and take all actions necessary and appropriate to implement the Compact.
30 (b) Except as otherwise provided in this Compact, venue is proper and judicial
31 proceedings by or against the Commission shall be brought solely and exclusively in a court of
32 competent jurisdiction where the principal office of the Commission is located. The Commission
33 may waive venue and jurisdictional defenses to the extent it adopts or consents to participate in
34 alternative dispute resolution proceedings. Nothing herein shall affect or limit the selection or
35 propriety of venue in any action against a licensee for professional malpractice, misconduct, or
36 any such similar matter.
37 (c) The Commission shall be entitled to receive service of process in any proceeding
38 regarding the enforcement or interpretation of the Compact and shall have standing to intervene
39 in such a proceeding for all purposes. Failure to provide service of process to the Commission
40 shall render a judgment or order void as to the Commission, this Compact, or promulgated rules.
41 (d) If the Commission determines that a member state has defaulted in the performance
42 of its obligations or responsibilities under this Compact or the promulgated rules, the
43 Commission shall do all of the following:
44 (1) Provide written notice to the defaulting state and other member states of the
45 nature of default, the proposed means of curing the default, and any other
46 action to be taken by the Commission.
47 (2) Provide remedial training and specific technical assistance regarding the
48 default.
49 (e) If a state in default fails to cure the default, the defaulting state may be terminated
50 from the Compact upon an affirmative vote of a majority of delegates of the member states, and
51 all rights, privileges, and benefits conferred by this Compact may be terminated on the effective
House Bill 231-First Edition Page 15

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 date of termination. A cure of the default does not relieve the offending state of obligations or
2 liabilities incurred during the period of default.
3 (f) Termination of membership in the Compact shall be imposed only after all other
4 means of securing compliance have been exhausted. Notice of intent to suspend or terminate
5 shall be given by the Commission to the governor, the majority and minority leaders of the
6 defaulting state's legislature, the defaulting state's state licensing authority and each of the
7 member states' state licensing authority. A state that has been terminated is responsible for all
8 assessments, obligations, and liabilities incurred through the effective date of termination,
9 including obligations that extend beyond the effective date of termination.
10 (g) Upon the termination of a state's membership from this Compact, that state shall
11 immediately provide notice to all licensees within that state of such termination. The terminated
12 state shall continue to recognize all licenses granted pursuant to this Compact for a minimum of
13 six months after the date of said notice of termination.
14 (h) The Commission shall not bear any costs related to a state that is found to be in default
15 or that has been terminated from the Compact, unless agreed upon in writing between the
16 Commission and the defaulting state.
17 (i) The defaulting state may appeal the action of the Commission by petitioning the U.S.
18 District Court for the District of Columbia or the federal district where the Commission has its
19 principal offices. The prevailing party shall be awarded all costs of such litigation, including
20 reasonable attorneys' fees.
21 (j) Upon request by a member state, the Commission shall attempt to resolve disputes
22 related to the Compact that arise among member states and between member and nonmember
23 states. The Commission shall promulgate a rule providing for both mediation and binding dispute
24 resolution for disputes as appropriate.
25 (k) By majority vote, the Commission may initiate legal action in the U.S. District Court
26 for the District of Columbia or the federal district where the Commission has its principal offices
27 against a member state in default to enforce compliance with the provisions of the Compact and
28 its promulgated rules and bylaws. The relief sought may include both injunctive relief and
29 damages. In the event judicial enforcement is necessary, the prevailing party shall be awarded all
30 costs of such litigation, including reasonable attorneys' fees. The remedies herein shall not be the
31 exclusive remedies of the Commission. The Commission may pursue any other remedies
32 available under federal or the defaulting member state's law.
33 (l) A member state may initiate legal action in the U.S. District Court for the District of
34 Columbia or the federal district where the Commission has its principal offices against the
35 Commission to enforce compliance with the provisions of the Compact and its promulgated rules
36 and bylaws. The relief sought may include both injunctive relief and damages. In the event
37 judicial enforcement is necessary, the prevailing party shall be awarded all costs of such
38 litigation, including reasonable attorneys' fees.
39 (m) No person other than a member state shall enforce this Compact against the
40 Commission.
41 "§ 90B-33. Effective date; withdrawal; amendment.
42 (a) The Compact shall come into effect on the date on which the Compact statute is
43 enacted into law in the seventh member state. On or after the effective date of the Compact, the
44 Commission shall convene and review the enactment of each of the first seven member states
45 (charter member states) to determine if the statute enacted by each such charter member state is
46 materially different than the model Compact statute.
47 (b) A charter member state whose enactment is found to be materially different from the
48 model Compact statute shall be entitled to the default process set forth in this Article. If any
49 member state is found to be in default, or is terminated or withdraws from the Compact, the
50 Commission shall remain in existence and the Compact shall remain in effect even if the number
51 of member states should be less than seven.
Page 16 House Bill 231-First Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) Member states enacting the Compact subsequent to the seven initial charter member
2 states shall be subject to the process set forth in this Article to determine if their enactments are
3 materially different from the model Compact statute and whether they qualify for participation
4 in the Compact.
5 (d) All actions taken for the benefit of the Commission or in furtherance of the purposes
6 of the administration of the Compact prior to the effective date of the Compact or the Commission
7 coming into existence shall be considered to be actions of the Commission unless specifically
8 repudiated by the Commission.
9 (e) Any state that joins the Compact subsequent to the Commission's initial adoption of
10 the rules shall be subject to the rules as they exist on the date on which the Compact becomes
11 law in that state. Any rule that has been previously adopted by the Commission shall have the
12 full force and effect of law on the day the Compact becomes law in that state.
13 (f) Any member state may withdraw from this Compact by enacting a statute repealing
14 the same. A member state's withdrawal shall not take effect until six months after enactment of
15 the repealing statute. Withdrawal shall not affect the continuing requirement of the withdrawing
16 state's licensing authority to comply with the investigative and adverse action reporting
17 requirements of this act prior to the effective date of withdrawal. Upon the enactment of a statute
18 withdrawing from this Compact, a state shall immediately provide notice of such withdrawal to
19 all licensees within that state. Notwithstanding any subsequent statutory enactment to the
20 contrary, such withdrawing state shall continue to recognize all licenses granted pursuant to this
21 Compact for a minimum of six months after the date of such notice of withdrawal.
22 (g) Nothing contained in this Compact shall be construed to invalidate or prevent any
23 licensure agreement or other cooperative arrangement between a member state and a nonmember
24 state that does not conflict with the provisions of this Compact.
25 (h) This Compact may be amended by the member states. No amendment to this Compact
26 shall become effective and binding upon any member state until it is enacted into the laws of all
27 member states.
28 "§ 90B-34. Construction and severability.
29 This Compact and the Commission's rulemaking authority shall be liberally construed so as
30 to effectuate the purposes, and the implementation and administration of the Compact. Provisions
31 of the Compact expressly authorizing or requiring the promulgation of rules shall not be
32 construed to limit the Commission's rulemaking authority solely for those purposes. The
33 provisions of this Compact shall be severable, and if any phrase, clause, sentence, or provision
34 of this Compact is held by a court of competent jurisdiction to be contrary to the constitution of
35 any member state, a state seeking participation in the Compact, or the United States, or the
36 applicability thereof to any government, agency, person, or circumstance is held to be
37 unconstitutional by a court of competent jurisdiction, the validity of the remainder of this
38 Compact and the applicability thereof to any other government, agency, person, or circumstance
39 shall not be affected thereby.
40 Notwithstanding this section, the Commission may deny a state's participation in the Compact
41 or, in accordance with the requirements of this Article, terminate a member state's participation
42 in the Compact, if it determines that a constitutional requirement of a member state is a material
43 departure from the Compact. Otherwise, if this Compact shall be held to be contrary to the
44 constitution of any member state, the Compact shall remain in full force and effect as to the
45 remaining member states and in full force and effect as to the member state affected as to all
46 severable matters.
47 "§ 90B-35. Consistent effect and conflict with other state laws.
48 A licensee providing services in a remote state under a multistate authorization to practice
49 shall adhere to the laws and regulations, including laws, regulations, and applicable standards, of
50 the remote state where the client is located at the time care is rendered. Nothing herein prevents
51 the enforcement of any other law of a member state that is not inconsistent with the Compact.
